ancelling-in-person-classes-due-to-coronavirus/|title=Universities cancelling in-person classes due to coronavirus|website=SowetanLIVE|language=en-ZA|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.up.ac.za/news/post_2881150-update-postponement-of-contact-classes-and-rescheduling-of-academic-calendar- |title = UPDATE: Postponement of contact classes and rescheduling of academic calendar}}</ref>\n*[[List of comic book conventions|Comic Con]] Cape Town, postponed to 2021.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.iol.co.za/entertainment/whats-on/cape-town/comic-con-cape-town-postponed-to-2021-45138721|title=Comic Con Cape Town postponed to 2021|website=www.iol.co.za|language=en|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n*Agricultural events such as the [[Pietermaritzburg]] Royal Show, SA Cheese Festival, Qualit\u00e9 Awards Dinner, and Agri-Expo Western Cape Youth Show, cancelled.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.foodformzansi.co.za/covid-19-farmers-urged-to-protect-themselves-workers/|title=COVID-19: Farmers urged to protect themselves, workers|last=Ngcakani|first=Noluthando|date=2020-03-16|website=Food For Mzansi|language=en-ZA|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n*[[Wimpy (restaurant)|Wimpy]] [[Lifesaving South Africa]], national championships cancelled.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.iol.co.za/sport/wimpy-lifesaving-south-africa-national-championships-cancelled-44956403|title=Wimpy Lifesaving South Africa National Championships cancelled|website=www.iol.co.za|language=en|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n*[[Scouts South Africa]], all Scouting activity suspended until schools reopen.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scouts.org.za/2020/03/16/scouting-suspended-in-response-to-covid-19/|title=Scouting suspended in response to COVID-19|website=www.scouts.org.za|date=16 March 2020|language=en|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n*The [[Johannesburg|City of Johannesburg]], all public facilities closed indefinitely including public swimming pools, recreational and civic centres, stadiums, libraries, sporting facilities, and the [[Johannesburg Zoo]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://citizen.co.za/news/south-africa/government/2257497/city-of-joburg-closes-all-public-facilities-including-pools-theatres-and-the-zoo/|title=City of Joburg closes all public facilities, including pools, theatres and the zoo |agency=News24 Wire |website=The Citizen|language=en|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n*The [[EThekwini Metropolitan Municipality|Ethekhwini Metropolitan Municipality]] closed all of [[Durban]]'s public facilities including swimming pools, beaches, libraries, community halls, and museums while restrictions have been put in place for the [[Durban Art Gallery]] and cemeteries to only allow 50 people at a time.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://businesstech.co.za/news/lifestyle/383319/durban-bans-swimming-at-the-beach/|title=Durban bans swimming at the beach|last=Writer|first=Staff|website=businesstech.co.za|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref>\n*[[Fake news]] spread to the effect that [[5G|5G cellular]] technology was the true cause of [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]] symptoms.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://citizen.co.za/lifestyle/technology/2263396/zweli-mkhize-says-5g-causing-covid-19-deaths-is-just-fake-news/|title=Zweli Mkhize says \u20185G causing Covid-19 deaths\u2019 is just fake news|last=Cilliers|first=Charles|website=The Citizen|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> \n\n===Travel===\nPresident [[Cyril Ramaphosa]] announced that from 18 March 2020, a travel ban will be imposed on foreign nationals travelling from high-risk countries and that visas for travellers from those countries have been cancelled.<ref name=\"presidency61\"/>\n\n====Bans====\n[[File:CoVid-19 South African travel bans.svg|thumb|right|Travel bans {{As of|alt=as of 2020-03-19.|2020|03|19}}]]\n*{{flagdeco|China}} [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic in mainland China|China]]\n*{{flagdeco|France}} [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in France|France]]<ref>{{Cite news\n|url=https://www.businessinsider.co.za/the-list-of-countries-with-travel-banned-to-south-africa-2020-3\n|title=France is now also on South Africa's Covid-19 travel ban list.\n|date=2020-03-19\n|publisher=Business Insider SA\n|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n*{{flagdeco|Germany}} [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Germany|Germany]]\n*{{flagdeco|Iran}} [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Iran|Iran]]\n*{{flagdeco|Italy}} [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Italy|Italy]]\n*{{flagdeco|South Korea}} [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in South Korea|South Korea]]\n*{{flagdeco|Spain}} [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Spain|Spain]]\n*{{flagdeco|UK}} [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom|UK]]\n*{{flagdeco|USA}} [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States|USA]]\n\n====Border post closures====\nFrom 16 March, 35 of 53 [[List of ports of entry in South Africa|land ports]] were shut down and 2 of the 8 sea ports were closed<ref name=\"presidency61\"/> for passengers and crew changes: [[Mossel Bay#Harbour|Mossel Bay]] and [[Saldanha, Western Cape#Port|Saldanha]].<ref name=\"bisa-ports\">{{cite news\n|title=Here are all the border posts South Africa is closing to combat Covid-19\n|url=https://www.businessinsider.co.za/these-are-the-border-posts-south-africa-is-closing-against-the-coronavirus-2020-3\n|accessdate=2020-03-16 |work=Business Insider South Africa}}</ref> On 19 March, it was announced by [[Minister of Public Works and Infrastructure (South Africa)|Minister of Public Works and Infrastructure]] [[Patricia de Lille]] that the government would erect and repair 40&nbsp;km of fencing to the east and west of the Beitbridge border post between South Africa and [[Zimbabwe]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://businesstech.co.za/news/government/383143/massive-border-fence-between-south-africa-and-zimbabwe-to-combat-coronavirus-spread/|title=Massive border fence between South Africa and Zimbabwe to combat coronavirus spread|last=News|first=S. A.|website=businesstech.co.za|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n\n====Advisories====\n[[File:CoVid-19 South African travel advisories.svg|thumb|right|Travel advisories {{as of|alt=as of 2020-03-15|2020|03|15}}]][[file:COVID-19 Outbreak World Map-Deaths.svg|thumb|right|Countries with confirmed cases (red) and deaths (black)]]Effective as of 15 March 2020, the government advised against all travel to China, the EU, Iran, South Korea, UK, and the USA; and discouraged all non-essential domestic travel, particularly by air, rail, taxi, and bus.<ref name=\"presidency61\"/>\n\n*{{flagdeco|China}} China\n*{{flagdeco|EU}} [[European Union]]\n**{{flagdeco|Austria}} [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Austria|Austria]]\n**{{flagdeco|Belgium}} [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Belgium|Belgium]]\n**{{flagdeco|Bulgaria}} [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Bulgaria|Bulgaria]]\n**{{flagdeco|Croatia}} [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Croatia|Croatia]]\n**{{flagdeco|Cyprus}} [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Cyprus|Cyprus]]\n**{{flagdeco|Czechia}} [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Czech Republic|Czechia]]\n**{{flagdeco|Denmark}} [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Denmark|Denmark]]\n**{{flagdeco|Estonia}} [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Estonia|Estonia]]\n**{{flagdeco|Finland}} [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Finland|Finland]]\n**{{flagdeco|France}} [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in France|France]]\n**{{flagdeco|Germany}} Germany\n**{{flagdeco|Greece}} [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Greece|Greece]]\n**{{flagdeco|Hungary}} [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Hungary|Hungary]]\n**{{flagdeco|Ireland}} [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Ireland|Ireland]]\n**{{flagdeco|Italy}} Italy\n**{{flagdeco|Latvia}} [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Latvia|Latvia]]\n**{{flagdeco|Lithuania}} [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Lithuania|Lithuania]]\n**{{flagdeco|Luxembourg}} [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Luxembourg|Luxembourg]]\n**{{flagdeco|Malta}} [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Malta|Malta]]\n**{{flagdeco|Netherlands}} [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Netherlands|Netherlands]]\n**{{flagdeco|Poland}} [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Poland|Poland]]\n**{{flagdeco|Portugal}} [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Portugal|Portugal]]\n**{{flagdeco|Romania}} [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Romania|Romania]]\n**{{flagdeco|Slovakia}} [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Slovakia|Slovakia]]\n**{{flagdeco|Slovenia}} [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Slovenia|Slovenia]]\n**{{flagdeco|Spain}} Spain\n**{{flagdeco|Sweden}} [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Sweden|Sweden]]\n*{{flagdeco|Iran}} Iran\n*{{flagdeco|South Korea}} South Korea\n*{{flagdeco|UK}} UK \n*{{flagdeco|USA}} USA\n\n===Economic impact===\nAt the beginning of the national shutdown on the 27 March South African economists predicted that the pandemic could cause a 2.5% to 10% contraction of [[Economy of South Africa|South Africa's total GDP]] in 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.moneyweb.co.za/news/economy/sa-economy-could-crater-up-to-10-this-year/|title=SA economy could crater up to 10% this year|date=2020-03-25|website=Moneyweb|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> The national lockdown and resulting economic slowdown reduced demand for electricity by more than 7 500 MW thereby temporarily reducing the impact of the long running [[South African energy crisis]].<ref>{{Cite web\n|url=https://www.iol.co.za/news/south-africa/gauteng/eskom-will-keep-the-lights-on-during-21-day-lockdown-45708578\n|title=Eskom will keep the lights on during 21-day lockdown\n|date=2020-03-28\n|publisher=Independent Media\n|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> \n\n====Stock market news====\nThe [[JSE Limited|JSE]] lost 15% of its value in the week ending 13 March 2020, its worst week in 21 years.<ref>{{cite news\n|url=https://www.businesslive.co.za/bd/markets/2020-03-13-market-wrap-jse-has-worst-week-since-1998-as-pandemic-plagues-investors/\n|title=MARKET WRAP: JSE has worst week since 1998 as pandemic plagues investors\n|date=2020-03-13\n|first1=Odwa\n|last1=Mjo\n|work=BusinessLIVE\n|accessdate=2020-03-16}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 March, the [[South African Reserve Bank]] governor, [[Lesetja Kganyago]] announced a reduction of the country's [[Repurchase agreement|repo rate]] by 100 basis points or 1 percentage point to 5.25%.<ref name=\"RepoSlashed\">{{cite web|url=https://www.moneyweb.co.za/news/south-africa/live-repo-rate-decision/|title=Repo rate slashed by 1%|last=Mar 2020|first=Suren Naidoo / 19|date=2020-03-19|website=Moneyweb|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref>\n\n====Banking and retail====\nRetailers like Clicks, [[Pick n Pay Stores|Pick n Pay]], and [[Woolworths Holdings Limited|Woolworths]] have some limitations on the number of the same items customers may buy.<ref>{{cite news\n|url=https://www.businessinsider.co.za/cornonavirus-linked-panic-buying-retailers-ration-stock-2020-3\n|title=Woolworths stops food demonstrations, limits items per customer - here's what other retailers are doing\n|date=2020-03-19\n|first1=Jay\n|last1=Caboz\n|publisher=Business Insider\n|accessdate=2020-03-19}}</ref> On 19 March, [[Minister of Trade and Industry (South Africa)|Minister of Trade and Industry]] [[Ebrahim Patel]] signed a government gazette that enforces [[price controls]] on essential items and that could see [[Price gouging|price gougers]] punished with measures including a R10 million fine, a fine equivalent to 10% of a firm's turnover, or [[Imprisonment|12 months in prison]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://businesstech.co.za/news/business/383217/new-regulations-bring-coronavirus-price-controls-for-certain-high-demand-products-heres-what-is-on-the-list/|title=New regulations bring coronavirus price controls for certain high-demand products \u2013 here's what is on the list|last=Writer|first=Staff|website=businesstech.co.za|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref> On 22 March, [[Standard Bank]] announced a 90-day [[Forbearance|payment holiday]] for small and medium-sized business and students to try and shield them from the economic impact of the outbreak, starting from 1 April.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.businessinsider.co.za/coronavirus-standard-bank-gives-businesses-a-debt-holiday-2020-3|title=Coronavirus: Standard Bank gives businesses, students a debt holiday|website=BusinessInsider|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.gov.za/taxonomy/term/707 South African government statements]\n*[http://www.nicd.ac.za/media/ NICD media]\n*[https://www.who.int/emergencies/diseases/novel-coronavirus-2019 WHO Coronavirus disease (COVID-19) outbreak]\n*[https://sacoronavirus.co.za/ Official government website for information about Coronavirus in South Africa]\n*[https://t.me/CoronaZABot Corona Telegram Bot for South Africa]\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in South Africa| ]]\n", "name_user": "TGCP", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eNational lockdown:ref", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_South_Africa"}
{"title_page": "J\u016btar\u014d", "text_new": "| name          = TINKU BABU\n| gender        = Male\n| language      = HINDI,ENGLISH\n| nickname      = BABU\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox given name\n| name          = J\u016btar\u014d\n| image         = \n| image_size    = \n| caption       = \n| pronunciation = \n| gender        = Male\n| meaning       = Different meanings depending on the [[kanji]] used\n| region        = \n| language      = \n| origin        = Japanese\n| alternative spelling = \n| nickname      = \n| variant forms =\n| related names = \n| name day      = \n| derived       = \n| popularity    = \n| footnotes     = \n}}\n'''J\u016btar\u014d''', '''Jutaro''' or '''Juutarou''' (written: \u91cd\u592a\u90ce, \u58fd\u592a\u90ce or \u53d7\u592a\u90ce) is a masculine Japanese given name. Notable people with the name include:\n\n*{{Nihongo|[[Jutaro Kimura]]|\u6728\u6751 \u91cd\u592a\u90ce||born 1968}}, Japanese baseball player\n*{{Nihongo|[[Komura Jutar\u014d]]|\u5c0f\u6751 \u58fd\u592a\u90ce||1855\u20131911}}, Japanese diplomat\n*{{Nihongo|[[Jutaro Kuroda]]|\u9ed2\u7530 \u91cd\u592a\u90ce||1887\u20131970}}, Japanese artist\n*{{Nihongo|[[Jutaro Nakao]]|\u4e2d\u5c3e \u53d7\u592a\u90ce||born 1970}}, Japanese mixed martial artist\n\n{{given name}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jutaro}}\n[[Category:Japanese masculine given names]]\n", "name_user": "TINKU BABU7", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Facebook ,you tube ,twitter,Watsapp etc)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/J%C5%ABtar%C5%8D"}
{"title_page": "Cyrus K. Holliday", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name    = Cyrus K. Holliday\n| image      = Cyrus K Holliday.jpg\n| caption   =\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date|1826|4|3|mf=y}}\n| birth_place  = [[Kidderminster, Pennsylvania|Kidderminster]], [[Pennsylvania]], U.S.\n| death_date   = {{death date and age|1900|3|29|1826|4|3|mf=y}}\n| death_place  =Topeka, Kansas, U.S.\n| occupation      = [[rail transport|Railroad]] executive\n| parents         = David Holliday<br>Mary (Kennedy) Holliday\n| spouse          = Mary Dillon Jones\n| children        = Lillie Holliday<br>Charles King Holliday\n}}\nColonel '''Cyrus Kurtz Holliday''' (April 3, 1826 &ndash; March 29, 1900) was an American railroad executive who was one of the founders of the township of [[Topeka, Kansas]], in the mid 19th century;<ref name=\"findagrave\">{{cite web| work=Findagrave.com| url=https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/6532533| title=Cyrus K. Holliday| accessdate=December 7, 2005}}</ref><ref name=\"History of Kansas\">{{cite book| title=A Standard History of Kansas and Kansans| chapterurl=http://skyways.lib.ks.us/genweb/archives/1918ks/bioh/hollidck.html| chapter=Cyrus K. Holliday|author1=Connelly, William E.  | location=Chicago| publisher=Lewis Publishing Company| year=1918; transcribed 1997 }}</ref>  and was [[Adjutant General of Kansas]] during the [[American Civil War]]. The title ''Colonel'', however, was honorary. He was the first president of the [[Atchison, Topeka and Santa Fe Railway]], as well as one of the railroad's directors for nearly 40 years, up to 1900. A number of railway locomotives have been named after him, as well as the former town of [[Holliday, Kansas]]. He was also the Deputy Grand Master of the [[Grand Lodge of Kansas|Grand Lodge A.F. & A.M. of Kansas]]. As a Freemason, he was a member of Topeka Lodge #17 and was highly influential in the decision of moving the State Capitol to the city of Topeka. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.masonic.benemerito.net/msricf/papers/marples/marples-unionpacific.freemasonry.nebraska.pdf|title=UNION  PACIFIC, FREEMASONRY,  AND  NEBRASKA|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==Education and early career==\nHe was born on April 3, 1826, to David and Mary (Kennedy) Holliday, in [[Kidderminster, Pennsylvania|Kidderminster]], [[Pennsylvania]] (near [[Carlisle, Pennsylvania|Carlisle]]).<ref name=\"History of Kansas\" /><ref name=Waters24>Waters, p. 24.</ref><ref name=\"Territorial Kansas\">{{cite web| work=Territorial Kansas Online| date=September 16, 2003| url=http://www.territorialkansasonline.org/cgiwrap/imlskto/index.php?SCREEN=bio_sketches/holliday_cyrus| title=Cyrus K. Holliday, 1826-1900| accessdate=March 27, 2007}}</ref> The younger Holliday received a public school education, graduating from [[Allegheny College]] in [[Meadville, Pennsylvania]], where he studied law, in 1852. Although he moved to [[Kansas]] in 1854, Allegheny College's alumni records show Holliday receiving a master's degree in 1855.<ref name=Waters24 />\n\nWhile he was still in Meadville, he was asked to prepare legal documentation for a new railroad that would connect to the city. The proposed railroad (likely the [[Pittsburgh and Erie Railroad]] which was sometimes known as \"The Meadville Line\") would almost connect with a larger nearby system (the [[Atlantic and Great Western Railroad]]), which meant that it could become a feeder route to the larger railroad. Holliday saw the potential of the line and instead of asking for a standard fee to create the documents, he asked for and was granted a partnership in the new railroad. When this railroad was purchased by the larger system, Holliday earned [[United States dollar|$]]20,000 from the sale.<ref name=\"History of Kansas\" />\n\nAfter the sale was completed, he married Mary Dillon Jones. He soon followed the many others making the migration to settle land west of the [[Mississippi River]], but Mary stayed behind in Pennsylvania. The two were reunited later in Kansas after the births of their children, Lillie and Charles King.\n\n==Founding Topeka and military service==\nIn 1854 he moved to Kansas, leaving his wife behind in Pennsylvania to follow later.  He first settled in [[Lawrence, Kansas|Lawrence]] in October 1854. On December 10, 1854, after helping to find a location for the new townsite of Topeka, he wrote a letter to his wife saying:\n\n<blockquote>I am now thirty miles above Lawrence on the Kansas River assisting in starting a new town. We are just about in the central portion of the \"settled\" Territory and with perhaps the best landing and the most eligible site for a city in the entire country. ... So I think it must be, and in a few years when civilization by its magic influence shall have transformed this glorious country from what it is now to the brilliant destiny awaiting it, the Sun in all his course will visit no land more truly lovely and desirable than this. Here, Mary, with God's kind permission, we will make our home; and I have every reason to believe a home it will truly be.<ref>{{cite web| publisher=The Capital-Journal| date=March 8, 2003| url=http://cjonline.com/stories/030903/our_hollidaytext.shtml| title=Cyrus K. Holliday -- A letter home| accessdate=July 4, 2005| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040223193936/http://cjonline.com/stories/030903/our_hollidaytext.shtml| archive-date=February 23, 2004| url-status=dead}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nIn 1855 Holliday received the honorary title of Colonel for supervising a regiment during the [[Wakarusa War]].  He also served as the [[Adjutant General of Kansas]] during the [[American Civil War|Civil War]] from May 2, 1864 to March 31, 1865.  Although his Colonel title was only honorary, he continued to use it long after his military service.<ref name=\"Territorial Kansas\" />\n\nIn 1861, Holliday served in the [[Kansas State Senate]], and although he ran for Congress in 1874, he was defeated in that election. He was a Republican.<ref name=\"History of Kansas\" />\n\nHolliday had broad interests in developing the natural resources of Kansas. In the 1890s he became mistakenly convinced that Ellis and Trego counties in central Kansas contained mineral deposits of [[tin]], [[zinc]], and [[gold]]. In 1899 his son [[Charles K. Holliday]] founded [[Smoky Hill City, Kansas]] near the supposed mineral deposits.<ref>{{cite journal| author=Plazak, Dan| year=2007| title=The imaginary gold mines of Kansas| journal=Mining History Journal| volume=14| pages=11\u201322 }}</ref>\n\n==Santa Fe Railroad==\nOnce Topeka was founded, it needed transportation to connect it to the rest of the country.  Holliday's legal skills were called on again to create the paperwork for a new railroad. In 1859 he singlehandedly wrote the charter for the Atchison and Topeka Railroad Company, which would connect the two cities by rail following the route of the [[Santa Fe Trail]].<ref name=Waters26>Waters, p. 26.</ref><ref>{{cite book| title=The story of the Santa Fe| page=[https://archive.org/details/storysantafe00bradgoog/page/n64 56]| author=Bradley, Glenn D.| location=Boston| publisher=The Gorham Press| year=1920| url=https://archive.org/details/storysantafe00bradgoog| accessdate=March 3, 2010}}</ref><ref name=Blackmar>{{cite book| pages=863\u2013864| url=https://books.google.com/?id=o8X5krq3fP8C| accessdate=March 3, 2010| title=Kansas: A Cyclopedia of State History, Embracing Events, Institutions, Industries, Counties, Cities, Towns, Prominent Persons, Etc.| editor=Blackmar, Frank W.| volume=II| location=Chicago| publisher=Standard Publishing Company| year=1912 }}</ref>  Kansas Territory governor [[Samuel Medary]] approved the charter on February 11, 1859.<ref name=Waters487>Waters, p. 487.</ref>  Holliday was named a director and president of the new railroad on September 17, 1860,<ref name=Waters24 /><ref name=SFPresidents>{{cite journal| title=Santa Fe Officials Past and Present| page=63| journal=Santa Fe Employes' Magazine|date=January 1910| volume=IV| issue=2| url=https://books.google.com/?id=vABLAAAAYAAJ| accessdate=March 3, 2010| publisher=Santa Fe Magazine }}</ref> which was renamed in 1863 to the [[Atchison, Topeka and Santa Fe Railroad]].  During his tenure as president, Holliday secured land grants from the federal government that would soon be used by the railroad to populate the western portion of Kansas in order to build a customer base for the railroad. He stepped down from the presidency at the end of 1863,<ref name=SFPresidents /> but remained on the board of directors until July 27, 1865. He rejoined the board on September 24, 1868, this time serving until his death on March 29, 1900.<ref name=Blackmar /><ref name=SFPresidents /><ref name=Waters346>Waters, p. 346.</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\n[[File:Officials at Fair Park, Atchison, Topeka, & Santa Fe, 'Cyrus K. Holliday' Locomotive No. 1 with Tender.jpg|thumb|upright|Officials of the Atchison, Topeka, & Santa Fe, on the line's ''Cyrus K. Holliday'' Locomotive No. 1]]\nHolliday is buried in Topeka Cemetery, [[Topeka, Kansas]].<ref name=\"findagrave\" /> He is memorialized for his contributions to [[Kansas]] and the Santa Fe:\n* ''Cyrus K. Holliday'', Locomotive #1, a vintage locomotive was displayed by the A, T & SF into the 1960s. The locomotive is now preserved in the Kansas History Museum as Santa Fe No. 132.\n* He is portrayed in the 1940 movie \"[[Santa Fe Trail (film)|Santa Fe Trail]]\" by [[Henry O'Neill]] as a promoter of commerce and development in the American West of his time.\n* {{libship honor|name=Cyrus K. Holliday|type=his}}<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.usmm.org/libertyships.html| title=Liberty Ships built by the United States Maritime Commission in World War II| accessdate=March 27, 2007| publisher=American Merchant Marine at War}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.kancoll.org/khq/1947/47_2_henderson.htm| title=Ships in World War II Bearing Kansas Names| author=Henderson, Harold J.| date=May 1947| publisher=Kansas State Historical Society| work=KanColl: The Kansas Historical Quarterlies| accessdate=March 27, 2007}}</ref>\n* Locomotive #1 on the [[Disneyland Railroad]] bore the name \"C.K. Holliday\" since the park's opening in 1955.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.disneylandtoday.com/Railroad/e1train.htm| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20010423122443/http://www.disneylandtoday.com/Railroad/e1train.htm| url-status=dead| archive-date=April 23, 2001| title=C.K. Holliday - Engine No. 1| work=The Happiest Place on Earth: The Santa Fe and Disneyland Railroad}}</ref>\n* Locomotive #2 of the [[Disneyland Railroad (Paris)|Euro Disneyland Railroad]] was also named \"C.K. Holliday\" in his honor.\n* In 1960, he was inducted into the [[Hall of Great Westerners]] of the [[National Cowboy & Western Heritage Museum]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Hall of Great Westerners |url=https://nationalcowboymuseum.org/hall-of-great-westerners/ |website=National Cowboy & Western Heritage Museum |accessdate=November 22, 2019}}</ref>\n* The Cyrus Hotel, opening in January 2019, has been named in his honor in Topeka, KS.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n* {{cite book| author=Waters, Lawrence Leslie| year=1950| title=Steel Trails to Santa Fe| publisher=University of Kansas Press, Lawrence, Kansas }}\n\n{{S-start}}\n\n{{S-new}}\n{{S-ttl| title=President of the [[Atchison, Topeka and Santa Fe Railway]]| years=1860 &ndash; 1863 }}\n{{S-aft| after=[[Samuel C. Pomeroy]] }}\n\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{good article}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Holliday, Cyrus K.}}\n[[Category:1826 births]]\n[[Category:1900 deaths]]\n[[Category:Atchison, Topeka and Santa Fe Railway presidents]]\n[[Category:American city founders]]\n[[Category:Kansas state senators]]\n[[Category:Mayors of Topeka, Kansas]]\n[[Category:Kansas Republicans]]\n[[Category:19th-century American politicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name    = Cyrus K. Holliday\n| image      = Cyrus K Holliday.jpg\n| caption   =\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date|1826|4|3|mf=y}}\n| birth_place  = [[Kidderminster, Pennsylvania|Kidderminster]], [[Pennsylvania]], U.S.\n| death_date   = {{death date and age|1900|3|29|1826|4|3|mf=y}}\n| death_place  =Topeka, Kansas, U.S.\n| occupation      = [[rail transport|Railroad]] executive\n| parents         = David Holliday<br>Mary (Kennedy) Holliday\n| spouse          = Mary Dillon Jones\n| children        = Lillie Holliday<br>Charles King Holliday\n}}\nColonel '''Cyrus Kurtz Holliday''' (April 3, 1826 &ndash; March 29, 1900) was an American railroad executive who was one of the founders of the township of [[Topeka, Kansas]], in the mid 19th century;<ref name=\"findagrave\">{{cite web| work=Findagrave.com| url=https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/6532533| title=Cyrus K. Holliday| accessdate=December 7, 2005}}</ref><ref name=\"History of Kansas\">{{cite book| title=A Standard History of Kansas and Kansans| chapterurl=http://skyways.lib.ks.us/genweb/archives/1918ks/bioh/hollidck.html| chapter=Cyrus K. Holliday|author1=Connelly, William E.  | location=Chicago| publisher=Lewis Publishing Company| year=1918; transcribed 1997 }}</ref>  and was [[Adjutant General of Kansas]] during the [[American Civil War]]. The title ''Colonel'', however, was honorary. He was the first president of the [[Atchison, Topeka and Santa Fe Railway]], as well as one of the railroad's directors for nearly 40 years, up to 1900. A number of railway locomotives have been named after him, as well as the former town of [[Holliday, Kansas]]. He was also the Deputy Grand Master of the [[Grand Lodge of Kansas|Grand Lodge A.F. & A.M. of Kansas]]. As a Freemason, he was a member of Topeka Lodge #17 and was highly influential in the decision of moving the State Capitol to the city of Topeka. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.masonic.benemerito.net/msricf/papers/marples/marples-unionpacific.freemasonry.nebraska.pdf|title=UNION  PACIFIC, FREEMASONRY,  AND  NEBRASKA|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==Education and early career==\nHe was born on April 3, 1826, to David and Mary (Kennedy) Holliday, in [[Kidderminster, Pennsylvania|Kidderminster]], [[Pennsylvania]] (near [[Carlisle, Pennsylvania|Carlisle]]).<ref name=\"History of Kansas\" /><ref name=Waters24>Waters, p. 24.</ref><ref name=\"Territorial Kansas\">{{cite web| work=Territorial Kansas Online| date=September 16, 2003| url=http://www.territorialkansasonline.org/cgiwrap/imlskto/index.php?SCREEN=bio_sketches/holliday_cyrus| title=Cyrus K. Holliday, 1826-1900| accessdate=March 27, 2007}}</ref> The younger Holliday received a public school education, graduating from [[Allegheny College]] in [[Meadville, Pennsylvania]], where he studied law, in 1852. Although he moved to [[Kansas]] in 1854, Allegheny College's alumni records show Holliday receiving a master's degree in 1855.<ref name=Waters24 />\n\nWhile he was still in Meadville, he was asked to prepare legal documentation for a new railroad that would connect to the city. The proposed railroad (likely the [[Pittsburgh and Erie Railroad]] which was sometimes known as \"The Meadville Line\") would almost connect with a larger nearby system (the [[Atlantic and Great Western Railroad]]), which meant that it could become a feeder route to the larger railroad. Holliday saw the potential of the line and instead of asking for a standard fee to create the documents, he asked for and was granted a partnership in the new railroad. When this railroad was purchased by the larger system, Holliday earned [[United States dollar|$]]20,000 from the sale.<ref name=\"History of Kansas\" />\n\nAfter the sale was completed, he married Mary Dillon Jones. He soon followed the many others making the migration to settle land west of the [[Mississippi River]], but Mary stayed behind in Pennsylvania. The two were reunited later in Kansas after the births of their children, Lillie and Charles King.\n\n==Founding Topeka and military service==\nIn 1854 he moved to Kansas, leaving his wife behind in Pennsylvania to follow later.  He first settled in [[Lawrence, Kansas|Lawrence]] in October 1854. On December 10, 1854, after helping to find a location for the new townsite of Topeka, he wrote a letter to his wife saying:\n\n<blockquote>I am now thirty miles above Lawrence on the Kansas River assisting in starting a new town. We are just about in the central portion of the \"settled\" Territory and with perhaps the best landing and the most eligible site for a city in the entire country. ... So I think it must be, and in a few years when civilization by its magic influence shall have transformed this glorious country from what it is now to the brilliant destiny awaiting it, the Sun in all his course will visit no land more truly lovely and desirable than this. Here, Mary, with God's kind permission, we will make our home; and I have every reason to believe a home it will truly be.<ref>{{cite web| publisher=The Capital-Journal| date=March 8, 2003| url=http://cjonline.com/stories/030903/our_hollidaytext.shtml| title=Cyrus K. Holliday -- A letter home| accessdate=July 4, 2005| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040223193936/http://cjonline.com/stories/030903/our_hollidaytext.shtml| archive-date=February 23, 2004| url-status=dead}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nIn 1855 Holliday received the honorary title of Colonel for supervising a regiment during the [[Wakarusa War]].  He also served as the [[Adjutant General of Kansas]] during the [[American Civil War|Civil War]] from May 2, 1864 to March 31, 1865.  Although his Colonel title was only honorary, he continued to use it long after his military service.<ref name=\"Territorial Kansas\" />\n\nIn 1861, Holliday served in the [[Kansas State Senate]], and although he ran for Congress in 1874, he was defeated in that election. He was a Republican.<ref name=\"History of Kansas\" />\n\nHolliday had broad interests in developing the natural resources of Kansas. In the 1890s he became mistakenly convinced that Ellis and Trego counties in central Kansas contained mineral deposits of [[tin]], [[zinc]], and [[gold]]. In 1899 his son [[Charles K. Holliday]] founded [[Smoky Hill City, Kansas]] near the supposed mineral deposits.<ref>{{cite journal| author=Plazak, Dan| year=2007| title=The imaginary gold mines of Kansas| journal=Mining History Journal| volume=14| pages=11\u201322 }}</ref>\n\n==Santa Fe Railroad==\nOnce Topeka was founded, it needed transportation to connect it to the rest of the country.  Holliday's legal skills were called on again to create the paperwork for a new railroad. In 1859 he singlehandedly wrote the charter for the Atchison and Topeka Railroad Company, which would connect the two cities by rail following the route of the [[Santa Fe Trail]].<ref name=Waters26>Waters, p. 26.</ref><ref>{{cite book| title=The story of the Santa Fe| page=[https://archive.org/details/storysantafe00bradgoog/page/n64 56]| author=Bradley, Glenn D.| location=Boston| publisher=The Gorham Press| year=1920| url=https://archive.org/details/storysantafe00bradgoog| accessdate=March 3, 2010}}</ref><ref name=Blackmar>{{cite book| pages=863\u2013864| url=https://books.google.com/?id=o8X5krq3fP8C| accessdate=March 3, 2010| title=Kansas: A Cyclopedia of State History, Embracing Events, Institutions, Industries, Counties, Cities, Towns, Prominent Persons, Etc.| editor=Blackmar, Frank W.| volume=II| location=Chicago| publisher=Standard Publishing Company| year=1912 }}</ref>  Kansas Territory governor [[Samuel Medary]] approved the charter on February 11, 1859.<ref name=Waters487>Waters, p. 487.</ref>  Holliday was named a director and president of the new railroad on September 17, 1860,<ref name=Waters24 /><ref name=SFPresidents>{{cite journal| title=Santa Fe Officials Past and Present| page=63| journal=Santa Fe Employes' Magazine|date=January 1910| volume=IV| issue=2| url=https://books.google.com/?id=vABLAAAAYAAJ| accessdate=March 3, 2010| publisher=Santa Fe Magazine }}</ref> which was renamed in 1863 to the [[Atchison, Topeka and Santa Fe Railroad]].  During his tenure as president, Holliday secured land grants from the federal government that would soon be used by the railroad to populate the western portion of Kansas in order to build a customer base for the railroad. He stepped down from the presidency at the end of 1863,<ref name=SFPresidents /> but remained on the board of directors until July 27, 1865. He rejoined the board on September 24, 1868, this time serving until his death on March 29, 1900.<ref name=Blackmar /><ref name=SFPresidents /><ref name=Waters346>Waters, p. 346.</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\n[[File:Officials at Fair Park, Atchison, Topeka, & Santa Fe, 'Cyrus K. Holliday' Locomotive No. 1 with Tender.jpg|thumb|upright|Officials of the Atchison, Topeka, & Santa Fe, on the line's ''Cyrus K. Holliday'' Locomotive No. 1]]\nHolliday is buried in Topeka Cemetery, [[Topeka, Kansas]].<ref name=\"findagrave\" /> He is memorialized for his contributions to [[Kansas]] and the Santa Fe:\n* ''Cyrus K. Holliday'', Locomotive #1, a vintage locomotive was displayed by the A, T & SF into the 1960s. The locomotive is now preserved in the Kansas History Museum as Santa Fe No. 132.\n* He is portrayed in the 1940 movie \"[[Santa Fe Trail (film)|Santa Fe Trail]]\" by [[Henry O'Neill]] as a promoter of commerce and development in the American West of his time.\n* {{libship honor|name=Cyrus K. Holliday|type=his}}<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.usmm.org/libertyships.html| title=Liberty Ships built by the United States Maritime Commission in World War II| accessdate=March 27, 2007| publisher=American Merchant Marine at War}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.kancoll.org/khq/1947/47_2_henderson.htm| title=Ships in World War II Bearing Kansas Names| author=Henderson, Harold J.| date=May 1947| publisher=Kansas State Historical Society| work=KanColl: The Kansas Historical Quarterlies| accessdate=March 27, 2007}}</ref>\n* Locomotive #1 on the [[Disneyland Railroad]] bore the name \"C.K. Holliday\" since the park's opening in 1955.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.disneylandtoday.com/Railroad/e1train.htm| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20010423122443/http://www.disneylandtoday.com/Railroad/e1train.htm| url-status=dead| archive-date=2001-04-23| title=C.K. Holliday - Engine No. 1| work=The Happiest Place on Earth: The Santa Fe and Disneyland Railroad}}</ref>\n* Locomotive #2 of the [[Disneyland Railroad (Paris)|Euro Disneyland Railroad]] was also named \"C.K. Holliday\" in his honor.\n* In 1960, he was inducted into the [[Hall of Great Westerners]] of the [[National Cowboy & Western Heritage Museum]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Hall of Great Westerners |url=https://nationalcowboymuseum.org/hall-of-great-westerners/ |website=National Cowboy & Western Heritage Museum |accessdate=November 22, 2019}}</ref>\n* The Cyrus Hotel, opening in January 2019, has been named in his honor in Topeka, KS.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n* {{cite book| author=Waters, Lawrence Leslie| year=1950| title=Steel Trails to Santa Fe| publisher=University of Kansas Press, Lawrence, Kansas }}\n\n{{S-start}}\n\n{{S-new}}\n{{S-ttl| title=President of the [[Atchison, Topeka and Santa Fe Railway]]| years=1860 &ndash; 1863 }}\n{{S-aft| after=[[Samuel C. Pomeroy]] }}\n\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{good article}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Holliday, Cyrus K.}}\n[[Category:1826 births]]\n[[Category:1900 deaths]]\n[[Category:Atchison, Topeka and Santa Fe Railway presidents]]\n[[Category:American city founders]]\n[[Category:Kansas state senators]]\n[[Category:Mayors of Topeka, Kansas]]\n[[Category:Kansas Republicans]]\n[[Category:19th-century American politicians]]\n", "name_user": "GiantSnowman", "label": "safe", "comment": "date formats perMOS:DATEFORMATbyscript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cyrus_K._Holliday"}
